commitResults.messageBody:
Create AppointmentDateTime class to encapsulate the starting/ending
date and time of an appointment

The Appointment class has both starting and ending date/time so that it
can be checked against other appointments involving the same patient or
doctor to detect clashes. New appointments that clash with existing ones
should not be allowed to be added.

commitResults.messageBody:
Person class isSamePerson method currently returns true if
the two Person objects have the same name.

The Receptionist may encounter people with the same name,
and this can be an issue as they cannot add a person with
the same name.

Updating the isSamePerson method to adopt a less strict
check for duplicates by comparing not just the name but
the phone and email field as well. This means, this
method will only return true when the two Person objects
have the same name, email and phone field.

A person is unlikely to have the same name, phone and email
as another person. If the Receptionist try to add such
a person while such a person already exists, the prompt
will be helpful to identify if this person is already
registered in the system.

Person class is currently used as the main object
in the entire program.

As this project is being adapted to fit PlannerMD,
the main object of concern should be Patient,
which is an extension of the Person class with an
additional Risk field.

Some considerations took in place for this refactoring
was the possible addition of other classes like Doctor,
thus files like AddCommand.java are renamed to
AddPatientCommand.java and AddCommand.java becomes
an abstract class containing the keyword that
is used to add both types of classes. This is done
in consideration for adding mass operations
such as mass deleting different classes such as
Patients and Doctors.

Some noteworthy changes include changes to the JSON format
for Storage. Note that the key changed from "persons" to
"patients" in JsonSerializablePlannerMd.java. A "risk" key
is also added to JsonAdaptedPatient.java (previously
JsonAdaptedPerson.java).

The class NameContainsKeywordsPredicate
has also become a generic class in which the class
becomes NameContainsKeywordsPredicate<T extends Person>
implements Predicate<T>. This is to support the same
predicate checks for other classes with the name fields,
i.e. other classes which inherit from the Person class.

Note that at this commit the program is able to run
and perform the required funtions. The test suites
will be fixed in the subsequent commits to fix
the failing tests.
